Name: Sarah Johnson
Age: 23
Gender: Female
Occupation: Student
Ethnicity: Caucasian
Past Medical History: Diagnosed with cystic fibrosis at age 6, history of recurrent respiratory infections, has been hospitalized multiple times for exacerbations of her condition.

Case Report:
Sarah Johnson is a 23-year-old female who has been living with cystic fibrosis since age 6. She presents to the clinic with complaints of increased coughing, difficulty breathing, and decreased exercise tolerance. She reports that her symptoms have been gradually worsening over the past few months.

On examination, Sarah is noted to have decreased breath sounds and crackles on auscultation of her lungs. Spirometry shows a significant decrease in her forced expiratory volume in 1 second (FEV1) compared to her baseline. Her sputum is sent for culture, which grows Pseudomonas aeruginosa.

Sarah is admitted to the hospital for intravenous antibiotics and airway clearance therapy. She is started on a combination of ceftazidime and tobramycin, and is scheduled for daily chest physiotherapy and nebulized hypertonic saline. Occupation: Student
Ethnicity: Caucasian
Past Medical History: Cystic fibrosis, diagnosed at birth.

Case Report:

She has a history of chronic cough, shortness of breath, and difficulty breathing during physical activity.

She also received nebulized medications to open up her airways and improve breathing. Name: Sarah Johnson
Age: 24
Gender: Female
Occupation: Student
Ethnicity: Caucasian
Past Medical History: Diagnosed with cystic fibrosis at age 3, hospitalizations for exacerbations every few years, currently taking enzymes, inhaled medications, and occasional antibiotics.

Case Report:
Sarah Johnson is a 24-year-old Caucasian female with a past medical history of cystic fibrosis. She was diagnosed with the disease at the age of 3 and has been managing it with medications and regular check-ups with her pulmonologist. Sarah is currently a full-time student and has been managing her condition well while balancing her academic workload.

Recently, Sarah presented to the hospital with worsening shortness of breath and increased coughing. She reported feeling more fatigued than usual and had noticed a decrease in her ability to exercise. Upon examination, her oxygen saturation was found to be low and her lung function was decreased compared to her previous visit. A chest x-ray revealed increased inflammation in her lungs and a sputum culture grew Pseudomonas aeruginosa.

Sarah was admitted to the hospital for intravenous antibiotics and airway clearance therapies. She was closely monitored by her healthcare team, including her pulmonologist and respiratory therapist.

Name: Sarah Johnson
Age: 25
Gender: Female
Occupation: Student
Ethnicity: Caucasian
Past Medical History: Diagnosed with cystic fibrosis at age 3, has had multiple hospitalizations for respiratory infections, currently taking pancreatic enzymes and inhaled medications.

Case Report:

Sarah Johnson is a 25-year-old Caucasian female with a history of cystic fibrosis. She was diagnosed at age 3 and has since had multiple hospitalizations for respiratory infections. Sarah is currently a student and manages her cystic fibrosis with pancreatic enzymes and inhaled medications.

During her most recent hospitalization, Sarah presented with increased cough and shortness of breath. She reported a decrease in exercise tolerance and an increase in the amount of mucus she was coughing up. Upon examination, she was found to have decreased lung function and increased sputum production.
